snippet.textDisplay:
I might get some heat for this, but I honestly believe they thought Parks and Rec was gonna end at season 6. It has the time jump and alludes to a very positive future for Leslie Knope, and all the characters feel wrapped up in their own way. To me, it was a super satisfying conclusion.

....Then they announced that there would be one more season, which would be the last. It followed the time jump and seemed like they were just really pushing for ideas of where the gang would be in the future, like a really extended outro for every character that wasn't totally necessary. Some things, like Ron never telling Leslie the truth about his feelings early in the season seems incredibly unlikely and out of character (Ron was a tough guy, but he loved Leslie and was always very supportive and open with her, moreso than any other character in the show.) Things like that made me feel like maybe it should've ended with the season before.

I just feel like I'm the only person who feels this way lmao

snippet.textDisplay: it wasn’t a comedy but SKINS. it was way too long and i personally felt like it should’ve ended after the season two finale when all of the original cast had left for the most part and were written out well to supposedly have moved on to do their own things. i don’t think it was necessary for them to try to renew the show with effy and try to make it somewhat of a spinoff because i ended up disliking her character and the nature of her actions and in suit, most of the other characters. it ended up being a cycle of people making bad, poorly thought out decisions and good people becoming bad people and never learning from their actions or mistakes, but also never forgiving others when they make those same mistakes. i think it was even less effective for them to try to make a third generation of people who just do even worse things or the same exact things and felt regurgitated and boring. i think what really made me dislike it the most was the unreal and almost cartoony direction the show went in where it felt like it went from real problems that teens deal with and feel to either overdramatic issues or unreal issues that most people would just never face in everyday life. i think it begins to take away from the relatability and realness of the show and makes you feel less like you’re living with them and more like it’s just another teen drama, which is disappointing because that’s not how it starts out at all.
